<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-952-404  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 952 404.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 11 1989 n278 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US telecom policy needs unity. (federal policy on regional Bellholding companies)(Perspective) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Latham, Daniel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Federal telecommunications policy has become disjointed andchaotic since the ATandamp;T divestiture of 1984, which drasticallychanged the US telecommunications environment.andP;  The fullyintegrated information society promised by some, following thedivestiture, has not materialized.andP;  US District Courtinterpretations of technology inhibit the development ofintelligent networks.andP;  The growth of fiber optics andBell-operated information gateways will release new demand foreasy-to-use data services; broadband fiber-optic links may settlethe controversy over delivery of high definition television (HDTV)signals.andP;  Both the FCC and the National Telecommunications andInformation Administration (NTIA) recommend that restrictions oncross-ownership of telephone and cable-television systems belifted.andP;  A cohesive federal policy strategy accommodating dynamictechnology is needed for the 1990s.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationCommunications IndustryBell Regional Holding CompaniesLegal IssuesCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>